.TH DAFT 1 "June 2026" "daft" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
daft \- generative ambient MIDI engine driven by system resources
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B daft
.RB [ \-\-midi\-out
.IR PATH ]
.RB [ \-\-seed
.IR N ]
.RB [ \-\-root
.IR 0..11 ]
.RB [ \-\-mood
.IR bright | dark ]
.RB [ \-\-density
.IR PERCENT ]
.RB [ \-\-simulate
.IR TRACE ]
.RB [ \-\-sim\-minutes
.IR N ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B daft
is a headless daemon that plays endless, sparse, ambient generative music
in the manner of Brian Eno's
.IR "Music for Airports" .
Six independent voice layers (a drone, two harmonic beds, two melodic
fragments, and a chime) cycle with mutually incommensurate periods and
probabilistically select notes from a pentatonic palette over a root
drone, so any vertical combination of sounding notes stays consonant.
.PP
The machine's vital signs act as slowly integrated weather that steers
the music indirectly:
.IP \(bu 3
CPU load drives overall event density, multiplied by an autonomous
breathing tide with a 7\(en15 minute period.
.IP \(bu 3
Memory pressure pulls the upper voices into lower, darker registers.
.IP \(bu 3
Sustained network activity brightens the mode emphasis and timbre
(continuous controller 74).
.IP \(bu 3
Disk activity swells the drone's expression (continuous controller 11).
.PP
One mapping is deliberately legible: a network traffic burst may ring a
single distant chime, probabilistically and rate-limited to at most one
every eight seconds.
.PP
Metrics are read from
.I /proc
and normalized adaptively against a rolling 30-minute history, so the
program is musically alive on an idle laptop and a loaded server alike.
.PP
Output is a raw MIDI byte stream written with plain
.BR write (2)
to the path given by
.B \-\-midi\-out
\(em a rawmidi or OSS MIDI device, a FIFO, or a regular file. The program
links against no MIDI or audio libraries. Route the stream to any
General MIDI capable synthesizer.
.SH OPTIONS
Options are applied in command-line order; later options override
earlier ones.
.TP
.BI \-\-midi\-out " PATH"
Where to write MIDI bytes. In live mode this is opened for writing as a
stream; in simulation mode a Standard MIDI File is created at this path.
Default:
.IR /dev/midi .
.TP
.BI \-\-seed " N"
Decimal seed for the deterministic pseudo-random number generator.
Identical seed and identical metric input produce identical music.
.TP
.BI \-\-root " 0..11"
Pitch class of the tonal root: 0 = C, 1 = C#, ... 5 = F (default), ...
11 = B.
.TP
.BI \-\-mood " bright\fR|\fPdark"
Base palette emphasis.
.B bright
(default) leans on the root and fifth;
.B dark
emphasizes the relative minor over the same pitch-class set. The mood
also drifts slowly at runtime with network weather.
.TP
.BI \-\-density " PERCENT"
Overall event-density scale, 25\(en400 (default 100).
.TP
.BI \-\-simulate " TRACE"
Run in deterministic simulation: metrics come from the CSV file
.I TRACE
instead of
.IR /proc ,
time is a fake clock that fast-forwards, and output is a Standard MIDI
File. Eight hours render in well under a second.
.TP
.BI \-\-sim\-minutes " N"
Simulated duration in minutes, 1\(en6000. Defaults to 480 (eight hours)
when
.B \-\-simulate
is given.
.SH TRACE FORMAT
Each simulation trace line holds five comma-separated unsigned integers:
.PP
.RS
.EX
t_seconds,cpu_permille,mem_permille,net_Bps,disk_sps
.EE
.RE
.PP
Values hold until the next timestamped line. Lines not beginning with a
digit (headers, comments) are ignored.
.SH SIGNALS
On
.B SIGINT
or
.B SIGTERM
the daemon releases every sounding note, sends All Notes Off
(controller 123) on every channel, finalizes the output, and exits.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Clean shutdown (signal or completed simulation).
.TP
.B 1
Invalid arguments or runtime failure (the cause is logged to standard
error with a fixed message ID).
.SH EXAMPLES
Play live through the kernel's virtual MIDI card:
.PP
.RS
.EX
# modprobe snd-virmidi
# daft &
.EE
.RE
.PP
then connect the virtual rawmidi port to a software synthesizer such as
fluidsynth(1).
.PP
Render and audit a simulated eight-hour day:
.PP
.RS
.EX
$ tools/gen_trace.sh > trace.csv
$ daft --simulate trace.csv --midi-out day.mid --seed 42
$ tools/smfcheck day.mid 5
.EE
.RE
.PP
A darker palette rooted on D, slightly busier:
.PP
.RS
.EX
$ daft --root 2 --mood dark --density 150
.EE
.RE
.SH FILES
.TP
.I /dev/midi
Default MIDI output path (OSS MIDI emulation; provided on Linux by the
snd-virmidi or snd-seq-oss modules, or by real MIDI hardware).
.TP
.IR /proc/stat ", " /proc/meminfo ", " /proc/net/dev ", " /proc/diskstats
Live metric sources.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR fluidsynth (1),
.BR write (2)
